23 [32]. Partitive and quasi-partitive genitives are abundant, and osten there is no stress on the partitive notion, the phrase becoming equivalent, as in poetry (e. g. strata viarum, in Lucretius and Vergil), to a simple substantive and adjective.

(a) With neut. sing. : extremo anni, vi 27, 1 ; lubricum iuventae, vi 49, 3 ; per medium diei, xi 21, 23 post multum vulnerum, xii 56, 5 ; medio diei, xii 69, 1.

(b) With neut. plur.: simulationum falsa, vi 45, 5; castellorum ardua, xi 9, 1 3 incerta Oceani, xi 20, 2 ; montium edita, xii 56, 4.

(c) A substantive, accompanied by an adjective, is taken out of its natural case, and put in the partitive genitive: cunctis civium, xi 22, 4 5 adversis proeliorum (= adversis proeliis), vi 36, 33 so, prob- ably‚ provinciarum vectigalibus = the tribute-paying provinces, xi 22, 8.

(d) Such a genitive may stand without any word expressing partition being expressed: Caninius Gallus quindecimvirum, vi 12, 1.
